This flow will determine the last login time of a user in Active Directory. Before windows 2003 this information was not persisted between domain controllers, so all domain controller times are checked, and the most recent is taken.

Inputs\:
host - A domain controller to enumerate all domain controllers from.
DN - The Distinguished name of the user to get the last login time of.
baseDN - The base DN of your domain. For example DC\=domain,DC\=com for domain.com
username - username to use for LDAP queries.
password - password to use for LDAP queries.

Responses\:
success - Last Login time obtained.
failure - something went wrong.

Returns\:
The last Login time as a java formatted string.

Results\:
lastLoginTime - The last Login time as a java formatted string.

Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults".

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

Input Parameters\:
DN - The DN parameter used in the LDAPSearch operation.  This becomes the key used to find the result set.

Responses\:
value retrieved - The next value in the collection was retrieved and stored in the returnResult result.

c989eb3b-8f81-4d98-8144-5d33fd719fe1.70eab10b-58c3-494c-aea9-cb0ca4a13f7b.description=
Checks if a user is in an active directory group.

Inputs\:
host - the hostname of an active directory domain controller.
username - username for host.
password - password for username.
userDN - The DN of the user to check, for example\: CN\=John Doe,CN\=Users,DC\=Domain,DC\=com
groupDN - The DN of the group to check, for example\: CN\=Domain Users,CN\=Users,DC\=Domain,DC\=com

Responses\:
success - The userDN is a member of the groupDN
failure - the userDN is not a member of the groupDN

Responses\: isNull - if the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value. notNull - if some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. c989eb3b-8f81-4d98-8144-5d33fd719fe1.description=
This flow will find all users who have not logged in recently. All the users that have not logged in the last number of days specified by the "daysOld" input parameter.

Inputs\:
host - A domain controller to enumerate all domain controllers from.
DN - The Distinguished name to read users from.
baseDN - The base DN of your domain. For example DC\=domain,DC\=com for domain.com.
groupDN - The DN of the group to check, for example\: CN\=Domain Users,CN\=Users,DC\=Domain,DC\=com.
username - The username to use for LDAP queries.
password - The password to use for LDAP queries.
daysOld - Integer positive value, representing the number of days ago user must have logged in since in order to be considered active.

Primary Output\:
returnResult - A table containing the distinguished names, and the last login times of the users who are inactive. The first column is distinguished named. The rows are | delimited, and the columns are ; delimited.

Additional outputs\:
InactiveUsers -  A table containing the distinguished names, and the last login times of the users who are inactive.

Responses\:
success - No inactive users were found.
diagnosed - Inactive users were found.
failure - Something went wrong.

If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true. failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false. c989eb3b-8f81-4d98-8144-5d33fd719fe1.efffcf57-44ca-4232-ac57-01a94e4f2d81.prompt=Enter a value for value1 c989eb3b-8f81-4d98-8144-5d33fd719fe1.f040b67b-6c15-4d7b-bc44-d9cbdf6f3659.prompt=Enter a value for value1 c989eb3b-8f81-4d98-8144-5d33fd719fe1.fe414c50-be5e-420b-9a03-da4ff96ce6ce.description=
Searches for specific properties in LDAP. Returns a list of the values of the given properties for the first object that passes the filter (given in the corresponding input). The rest of the property values (for the other objects) are stored in a collection that is accessible via the LDAP Search Next Result operation.

Input Parameters\:
host - Name or IP address of LDAP server to query. Can also be used in the form " host\:port".
DN - Base DN for search.
filter - Search filter (see Note section).
propertyNames - Names of properties to return (ex. distinguishedName,telephoneNumber).
username - Name of user to connect to LDAP as.
password - Password of user.
port - Specify the port in case it is not the default one, or it is not specified in the host path.
delimiter - A delimiter to separate the property names in the input and the property values in the result. If no value is assigned the delimiter is set to "," by default.

Responses\:
success - was able to retrieve objects and property values from LDAP. First value returned as returnResult result
failure - either no objects were found, an invalid or duplicate property name was provided or an error occured. See returnResult for more information

Note\:
The filter input can be a simple filter, or a composed one. The filter can be composed by the rules described in "RFC2254 - The String Representation of LDAP Search Filters" which can be found at http\://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc2254.html.  

Example of valid filters\:
member\=CN\=User1,CN\=Users,DC\=mydomain,DC\=local
(|(numsubordinates\=1)(entryid\=15))
(&(mobile\=*)(name\=abcd))
(&(objectClass\=Person)(|(sn\=Jensen)(cn\=Babs J*)))
